"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391517","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-09","<p /> <p>The Ministry of Justice has not made any estimate of the number of criminal appeals departments in law firms that have closed since the changes to legal aid funding introduced in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 were introduced.</p><p>All Criminal Legal Aid Contract holders are entitled to undertake Criminal Appeals and Reviews work.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391517/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-09T11:27:51.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391517/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391517/answer",,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-20","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate has been made of the number of criminal appeals departments in law firms that have closed since the changes to legal aid funding introduced in the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 were introduced.","false","Biography information for John Pugh","Southport","John Pugh","8046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391518","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-09-07","<p /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>I responded to the Hon. Member for East Worthing and Shoreham on 8 June.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391518/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:39:58.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391518/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391518/answer",,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-07-20","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to respond to the email sent by the hon. Member for East Worthing and Shoreham on 13 May regarding the case of a constituent receiving inadequate support and provision on leaving jail, and the follow-up email sent in 17 June.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","8114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391519","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>In the September 2013 Spending Review, the Chancellor of the Exchequer announced funding to electrify the Barking to Gospel Oak line on which Woodgrange Park station is situated. Network Rail has already begun the extensive infrastructure work required to achieve this, and expects to complete the work in mid 2017. This upgrade will enable higher capacity electric trains to operate, facilitating more reliable services for passengers and freight, as well as reduced noise and pollution for line side neighbours.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Network Rail will also be working with Transport for London (TfL) to extend the platforms along the route. This means that London Overground will be able to operate new four-car electric trains as opposed to the current two-car diesel stock. TfL has now placed the order for the new trains and, following the route upgrade, it expects to introduce them onto the network from early 2018. This will almost double the passenger capacity of the existing service.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391519/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:01:30.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391519/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391519/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Woodgrange Park Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to improve passenger services through Woodgrange Park rail station.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391520","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The most recent cost of the proposed New Generation Trolleybus scheme in Leeds as provided to this Department by the promoters, the West Yorkshire Combined Authority, is £250 million.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391520/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:33:47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391520/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391520/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Trolleybuses: Leeds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent estimate he has made of the cost of the proposed New Generation Trolleybus scheme in Leeds.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391521","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Inspector who held an inquiry into this scheme between April and October last year submitted an extensive report to the Department on 29 July 2015. We are giving the report careful consideration and will publish it with a fully reasoned decision letter as soon as reasonably possible. Given the complex issues involved in this case it is too early to predict when that will be.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391521/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-10T13:58:20.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391521/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391521/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Trolleybuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made on the Inquiry Inspector's report following the public inquiry into the New Generation Trolleybus scheme; and when he plans to make a further announcement on that scheme.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","8087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391522","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>As reported previously in the Answer of 13 July 2015 to Question 5807 and the Answer of 14 July 2015 to Question 7026 by my Hon Friend, the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, the Hon Member for Devizes (Claire Perry), the initial work on the North Transpennine electrification business case comprises a range of scenarios. The latest assessment of the benefit cost ratio for electrification alone showed it was poor value for money but when it is combined with track improvements to provide faster journeys and more frequent services, it has the potential to be high value for money. There are no further updates to that answer at this time.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391522/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T10:41:50.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391522/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391522/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 21015 to Question 7026, what the cost-benefit ratio was for North TransPennine electrification programme on the most recent date for which figures are available; and what the cost-benefit ratio was for North TransPennine electrification programme when combined with track improvements on that date.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","8093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391523","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p>We are working hard to design the bidding process for the New Stations Fund and will announce the deadlines for the fund shortly.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391523/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T10:30:30.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391523/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391523/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Railway Stations: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 21015 to Question 6468, when the new round of bidding to the New Station Fund will (a) begin and (b) conclude.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","8092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391524","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-07","<p><br></p><p><strong>Mode Shift Revenue Support (MSRS) expenditure for rail freight moved in each year since the scheme started in April 2010, is shown in the table below. </strong></p><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total MSRS expenditure (including inland waterway)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£19,373,617</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,489,457</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,869,638</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,752,301</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£17,792,310</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>MSRS rail expenditure</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£19,373,617</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,439,868</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,752,664</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£16,622,583</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£17,691,643</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Rail as proportion of MSRS expenditure</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>100%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>99.70%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>99.30%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>99.23%</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>99.43%</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><br></p><p><strong>The MSRS scheme also covers inland waterways but not maritime freight. Mode shift support for coastal and short sea shipping is provided though a separate scheme, Waterborne Freight Grant, for which expenditure is shown in the table below. </strong></p><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Waterborne Freight Grant</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£240,594</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£81,770</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£416,349</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£557,878</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£283,741</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391524/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T12:01:07.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391524/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391524/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Freight: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much and what proportion of its expenditure the Mode Shift Revenue Support scheme granted to (a) rail and (b) maritime freight operators in each year since 2009-10.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","8000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391525","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport is aware that discussions are taking place between train operating companies and Transport for London (TfL) about possible changes to Pay As You Go fares in London, however we await the outcome of these discussions which we are not party to.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391525/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:54:28.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391525/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391525/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions his Department has had with Govia Thameslink Railway on the talks between London-based train operators and Transport for London aimed at sharing pay-as-you-go fares on suburban rail routes.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","7979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391526","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>Estimates of the number of passengers using each station on the rail network are published on the Office of Rail Regulation’s website at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/station-usage-estimates" target="_blank">http://orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/station-usage-estimates</a></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The methodology for this data set has changed over time as improvements have been made, so the estimates from different years may not have been produced on a consistent basis. Details of the methodology changes made each year can be found in the accompanying reports.</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391526/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:41:58.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391526/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391526/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Railway Stations: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people use each train station in (a) Copeland and (b) Cumbria each year.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391527","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport’s role is setting the annual parameters for regulated fare increases. The train operating company (TOC) is obliged to set fares within the limits set by the Secretary of State.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391527/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:51:24.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391527/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391527/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what role his Department has in setting fares on trains operated by Govia Thameslink Railway.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","7978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391528","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-10","<p>The Government recognises that this emerging technology has great opportunities for the UK. However the Government is aware that there have been a few incidents that have caused some concerns to other commercial air traffic.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Civil Aviation Authority has recently launched a publicity campaign called &quot;You have control. Be safe! Be legal!’’ which is aimed at raising awareness of the general public, at the point of purchase, about their responsibilities as the unmanned aircraft operator.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition to this a cross-government working group is currently engaged in a piece of work that is looking at the risks posed by drones to commercial civil aviation. The results of this work will inform our understanding of the scale of the problem and what steps need to be taken to mitigate these risks.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391528/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-10T15:09:16.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391528/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391528/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment has been made of the implications for his Department's policies of the increase in the number of privately owned drones and its effects on safety for civil aviation.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","7971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391529","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport for (a) have not given Govia Thameslink Railway any permission to vary ticket prices, but for (b) there are agreements in place which govern Oyster/PAYG fares within the Travelcard area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391529/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:46:28.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391529/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391529/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Railways: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 July 2015 to Question 4820 on railways: performance standards, what permission his Department has granted to Govia Thameslink Railway to (a) vary ticket prices and (b) enter into an agreement with Transport for London to share the same-pay-as-you-go fares on suburban rail routes in London.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","7902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391530","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-11","<p>This Government is committed to tackling poor air quality. Our aim is for almost every car and van to be a zero emission vehicle by 2050.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>£2 billion has been committed since 2011 to increase the uptake of ultra-low emission vehicles, green transport initiatives and supporting local authorities to take action. These measures will help address both particulate matter and nitrogen dioxide roadside levels in pollution hotspots.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391530/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-11T08:29:00.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391530/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391530/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-20","Motor Vehicles: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to tackle air pollution from road vehicles; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","7938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391531","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-09-09","<p>Location data for limit value exceedances is compiled at a zone level and has also been converted to local authority level to assist local authority air quality assessments. With over 1 million postcodes in the UK the information requested could only be converted into postcode level data at a disproportionate cost. 194 local authorities exceeded the annual mean limit values for nitrogen dioxide (NO<sub>2</sub>) in 2013. A list of these local authorities is attached.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391531/answer","519 - 7932 - Local Authority NO2 exceedances 2013.pdf","519 - 7932 - Local Authority NO2 exceedances 2013.pdf","Local authority exceedances 2013","Local authority exceedances 2013",,"2015-09-09T16:33:51.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391531/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391531/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-20","Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, in which post codes in the UK agreed limits for air pollution were breached in the most recent year available.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","7932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391532","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>Data on the number of households capped since April 2013 by region and family type can be found in Stat-Xplore, the Department’s online interactive tabulation tool, which can be accessed here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/opendatabase?id=Benefit_Cap_Cumulative" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/opendatabase?id=Benefit_Cap_Cumulative</a></p><p>Information on the number of children aged under 5 is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391532/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T15:54:05.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391532/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391532/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many lone parent families in Scotland have been affected by the benefit cap to date; and how many such families have (a) one child, (b) two and (c) three children under five.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","7931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391533","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. This includes details of review of the policies. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391533/answer",,,,,"8018","2015-09-08T16:12:30.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391533/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391533/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Welfare State: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to conduct an annual equalities impact assessment of the effect in Scotland of the welfare changes announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","7930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391534","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>As independent analysis by the Institute for Fiscal Studies has shown, the rise in women’s State Pension age since 2010 has been accompanied by increases in employment rates for the women affected. Those who are unable to work because of health problems may be able to claim Employment and Support Allowance, whilst those who are unemployed may be able to receive Jobseeker's Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>All those affected by faster equalisation will reach State Pension age after the introduction of the new State Pension. The new State Pension will be more generous for many women who have historically done poorly under the current, two-tier system, largely as a result of lower average earnings and part-time working. Around 650,000 women reaching State Pension age in the first ten years will receive an average of £8 per week (in 2014/15 earnings terms) more due to the new State Pension valuation of their National Insurance record.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391534/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:10:35.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391534/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391534/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Oral Question  of the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish of 15 July 2015, Official Report, column 889, on state pensions for women, if he will take steps to provide financial support to those women affected by those changes.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391535","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The Minister has not met formally with campaign group representatives but is in frequent contact with relevant stakeholders across her portfolio.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will not be revisiting the State Pension age timetable for women affected by the 2011 Act. Government carried out extensive analysis of the impacts of bringing forward the rise to 66 when legislating for the change. The decision to bring forward a Government amendment to the timetable originally set out in the bill, to cap the maximum increase at 18 months rather than 2 years, was informed by this analysis.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently preparing for the first State Pension age review, which will conclude by May 2017. Alongside updated life expectancy projections, this review will be informed by an independent report, which will consider wider factors that should be taken into account when setting State Pension age, such as healthy life expectancy, variations in life expectancy between different groups, and wider economic issues.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391535/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:15:05.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391535/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391535/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Oral Question  of the hon. Member for Denton and Reddish of 21 July 2015, Official Report, column 889, on state pensions for women, what recent discussions the Minister of State for Pensions has had with (a) his Ministerial colleagues and (b) campaign groups on the effect of those changes on women born in the 1950s.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391536","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>We have implemented a wide range of initiatives across the whole Personal Independence Payment (PIP) claiming journey to speed up processes and clear more claims and are continuing to identify further opportunities to drive forward improvements. Figures released on 17 June (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2015</a>) reflect the significant progress made over the past year and show claims for PIP are now being cleared at four times the rate they were in January 2014. The average new claimant now only waits for 5 weeks for an assessment, and the number of cases dealt with by the assessment providers has more than quadrupled in the last year.</p><p> </p><p>There are no delays in the payment of Universal Credit. All new claims assessed are processed within the required timescales.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391536/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:45:35.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391536/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391536/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to reduce delays in the payments of personal independence payments and universal credit.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","7914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391537","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>Increases to private sector pensions in payment will depend on the scheme rules. The Government sets a statutory minimum for the indexation of certain defined benefit pensions accrued between specific dates and, as long as schemes meet this minimum, they may choose how and when to increase pensions in payment and on what basis.</p><p> </p><p>In some cases rules may contain a requirement for specific increases; in others the trustees can exercise their discretion.</p><p> </p><p>It is, therefore, for the scheme to provide members with information about any changes to pensions in payment.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391537/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:02:43.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391537/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391537/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Pensions: Private Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish guidance for people with private sector pensions on the effect of decisions to change the basis on which pensions are uprated on those people.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","7912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391538","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The full employment clause in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill places a duty on the Secretary of State to lay a report before Parliament detailing progress towards full employment. The first annual report will set out the interpretation of full employment.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be appropriate to use the Europe 2020 strategy as the basis for defining full employment, as the UK employment rate for those aged 20-64, which currently stands at 76.5%, has already exceeded the target recommended in that report.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391538/answer",,,,,"7954","2015-09-08T14:51:45.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391538/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391538/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will adopt the definition of full employment used in the Europe 2020 strategy to define full employment in the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391539","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p>The full employment clause in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill places a duty on the Secretary of State to lay a report before Parliament detailing progress towards full employment. The first annual report will set out the interpretation of full employment.</p><p> </p><p>It would not be appropriate to use the Europe 2020 strategy as the basis for defining full employment, as the UK employment rate for those aged 20-64, which currently stands at 76.5%, has already exceeded the target recommended in that report.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391539/answer",,,,,"7953","2015-09-08T14:51:45.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391539/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391539/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures he plans to use to assess progress towards full employment.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391540","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>Estimates of the number and proportion of children in combined low income and material deprivation are published in the National Statistics Households Below Average Income (HBAI) series.</p><p> </p><p>Figures for combined low income and material deprivation have been published in HBAI since 2004/05 and are available up to 2013/14.</p><p> </p><p>The latest publication is available at the link below:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-19941995-to-20132014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-19941995-to-20132014</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391540/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T15:15:46.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391540/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391540/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the number of children experiencing material deprivation in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391541","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>We know work is the best route out of poverty, and this Government is committed to supporting parents to move into work, increase their earnings, and keep more of what they earn.</p><p> </p><p>We have repeatedly said that the Child Poverty Act does not address the root causes of poverty and focuses only on the symptoms. That is why we have set out proposals in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill which provide a new way to drive effective action and make a real difference in the lives of poor children – both now and in the future.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391541/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T15:00:25.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391541/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391541/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects to meet the four targets for eradicating child poverty as set out in the Child Poverty Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391542","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The Department is not setting targets for numbers in receipt of Universal Credit because numbers will vary according to factors such as economic circumstances and the behavioural change of claimants.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391542/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T16:20:43.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391542/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391542/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Universal Credit: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people in Scotland who will be claiming universal credit in April (a) 2016, (b) 2017, (c) 2018, (d) 2019 and (e) 2020.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","8002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391543","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. This includes details of review of the policies. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html" target="_blank">http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2015-16/welfarereformandwork/documents.html</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391543/answer",,,,,"7930","2015-09-08T16:12:30.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391543/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391543/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Welfare State: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will undertake an annual review of the effect in Scotland of the welfare changes announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","8018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391544","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391544/answer",,,,,"8003 ; 8105 ; 8106 ; 8109","2015-09-07T14:38:17.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391544/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391544/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Tooting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people living in Tooting constituency who are likely to move home because of a reduction in the benefit cap to £23,000.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391545","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391545/answer",,,,,"8003 ; 8106 ; 8107 ; 8109","2015-09-07T14:38:17.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391545/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391545/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Tooting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of children living in households in Tooting constituency likely to be affected by a reduction in the benefit cap to £23,000.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391546","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391546/answer",,,,,"8003 ; 8105 ; 8107 ; 8109","2015-09-07T14:38:17.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391546/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391546/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of children living in households in London likely to be affected by a reduction in the benefit cap to £23,000.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391547","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The UK already has an employment rate above the aim set out in the Europe 2020 Strategy. Estimates of the Non Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment have been made by the Office for Budget Responsibility. Estimates of the level of unemployment under other scenarios are not available as this depends on a variety of factors including the size of the population at the time that position is reached and how those not in work are split between unemployed and economically inactive.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391547/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T14:19:20.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391547/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391547/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who would remain unemployed when full employment is achieved under (a) the Non-Accelerating Inflation Rate of Unemployment, (b) the definition of full employment set out in the Europe 2020 Strategy, (c) the definition of full employment as the highest employment rate in the G7 and (d) the definition of full employment as the lowest rate of unemployment in the G7.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","8078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391548","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>There are no plans to collate such information.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391548/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T16:25:20.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391548/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391548/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2015 to Question 6479, if he will make it his policy to collect such data in future.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","8067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391549","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>Clause 4 of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill intends to place a new duty on the Secretary of State to report annually on children in workless households and the educational attainment of children.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391549/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T16:11:46.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391549/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391549/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to Clause 4 of the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, what steps he plans to take to ensure that incidence of children living in poverty in households where at least one adult in work is recorded and reported.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","8054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391550","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391550/answer",,,,,"8105 ; 8106 ; 8107 ; 8109","2015-09-07T14:38:16.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391550/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391550/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of households in Scotland which will be affected by the proposed decrease in the household benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","8003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391551","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>To prevent young people slipping straight into a life on benefits, from April 2017 the Government will remove the automatic entitlement to housing support for new claims in Universal Credit from 18-21 year olds who are out of work. This will ensure young people in the benefits system face the same choices as young people who work and who may not be able to afford to leave home.</p><p> </p><p>We will ensure that vulnerable young people who are in need of support for their housing needs continue to receive it. Government will consider the impact in line with our legal obligations as part of that process.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391551/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:55:36.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391551/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391551/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, who he plans will be exempt from the removal of automatic entitlement to housing benefit for people aged 18 to 21.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","8004"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391552","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>DWP is constantly seeking ways to improve services for people with Hidden Impairment (HI) conditions including Dyslexia. We recognise that, with appropriate reasonable adjustment support, many people with HI have the skills and talent to gain and keep employment.</p><p> </p><p>A claimant who has difficulty making their claim for benefit online because of dyslexia or a similar condition can call 0800 055 6688 and receive personal help.</p><p> </p><p>When such claimants need additional support to complete a job application, draft a CV or prepare for an interview, their Jobcentre Plus Work Coach can offer initial advice. Most Jobcentre Plus offices now have Claimant Computer Suites manned by Customer Service staff. These suites provide free internet access in Jobcentres to aid claimants in their job search activity and support them with the on-line claim process. Staff can use these facilities to help claimants to navigate around the internet and assist with job searches or on-line claims.</p><p> </p><p>If the individual requires further specialist support they could make an appointment with a Jobcentre Plus Disability Employment Adviser (DEA), or their Work Coach can signpost them to local sources of specialist support, such as Work Clubs, third sector organisations or the National Careers Service.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391552/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T15:23:11.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391552/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391552/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Dyslexia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department provides to claimants with dyslexia who need additional assistance when completing forms and applications.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","8050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391553","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The information is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391553/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T14:44:13.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391553/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391553/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Tooting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of how many people in Tooting constituency have moved home as a result of the implementation of the benefit cap.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391554","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill on 20th July. A link to the impact assessment on the <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk</a> website is included.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006.pdf</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391554/answer",,,,,"8003 ; 8105 ; 8106 ; 8107","2015-09-07T14:38:17.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391554/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391554/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Social Security Benefits: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people living in London who are likely to move home because of a reduction in the benefit cap to £23,000.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","8109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391555","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The table below shows the proportion of total Housing Benefit expenditure in Great Britain that was spent in England, Wales and Scotland over the last three years. Housing Benefit in Northern Ireland is a matter for the Northern Ireland Office.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>England</p></td><td><p>88%</p></td><td><p>89%</p></td><td><p>89%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wales</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td><td><p>4%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Scotland</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td><td><p>7%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Source: Local Authority subsidy returns</p><p>Notes:</p><p>1. Figures are rounded to nearest 1%, and do not sum to 100% in 2012/13.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391555/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T16:05:15.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391555/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391555/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of the gross value of all housing benefit payments was allocated to claimants in (a) England, (b) Northern Ireland, (c) Scotland and (d) Wales in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","8099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391556","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-08","<p /> <p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, Mr Iain Duncan Smith replied to the Rt. Hon. Member on 13 July 2015.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391556/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T16:59:16.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391556/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391556/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-20","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to reply to the letter to him dated 11 June 2015 from the right hon. Member for Manchester, Gorton, with regard to Mr R Koudsi.","false","Biography information for Sir Gerald Kaufman","Manchester, Gorton","Sir Gerald Kaufman","8121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390913","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-24","<p /> <p>We have had no such discussions. Royal Mail is required by regulation to ensure that it maintains fair and reasonable remedies and redress.</p><p> </p><p>Ofcom, the postal regulator, monitors the effectiveness of compensation arrangements and, if necessary, can direct Royal Mail to modify its Postal Schemes which cover charges and terms and conditions for its universal service products and services.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390913/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T14:20:40.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390913/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390913/answer",,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-17","Postal Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with representatives of Royal Mail on the adequacy of the postal compensation scheme; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","7762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390914","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-27","<p>The financial health of further education colleges is under constant review by the Skills Funding Agency based on self-assessment information from colleges and the publication of college accounts. Colleges with inadequate financial health are subject to intervention led by the FE Commissioner.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Across all our grant, loan and capital support for adult FE, we are making available over £3bn in 2015-16 and our funding mechanism is designed to allow providers the freedoms and flexibilities to decide how best to use their allocation to respond to local learner and employer demand. As autonomous organisations it is up to colleges to manage their own budgets.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are our priority for skills and colleges have been encouraged to expand their apprenticeship offer. As government funding has reduced, many colleges have responded well by looking at generating other income streams and creating sustainable business models for the future. This entrepreneurial approach will help ensure sustainable future business models with less reliance on government funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In order to address the significant financial pressures on institutions, a declining 16-19 population and the need to maintain very tight fiscal discipline in order to tackle the deficit, a major reform of post-16 education and training institutions is necessary. On 20 July the Departments for Education and Business, Innovation and Skills announced a programme of area-based reviews to review 16+ provision in every area. These reviews will provide an opportunity for institutions and localities to restructure their provision to ensure it is tailored to the changing context and designed to achieve maximum impact.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390914/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-27T10:49:55.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390914/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390914/answer",,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-17","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of changes to the adult skills budget on the long-term financial stability of the further education sector.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390915","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-23","<p>The European Fund for Strategic Investments (EFSI) is used to support projects that bear a higher risk than most of the European Investment Bank’s (EIB) lending activities. The EIB is working directly with applicants and will be assessing project proposals through its normal processes, to establish which projects are most appropriate for support under EFSI. EFSI does not require applicants to submit proposals through Government Departments.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390915/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T15:17:31.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390915/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390915/answer",,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-17","European Fund for Strategic Investments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proposals his Department have put forward for projects under the EU Fund for Strategic Investments.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390916","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-27","<p>The use of equipment and weapons supplied to the Saudis is an operational matter for the Saudi military authorities. The Saudis have assured us that British-supplied munitions will be used in compliance with international humanitarian law and we continue to engage with them on these assurances.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390916/answer",,,,,"7820","2015-07-27T13:48:29.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390916/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390916/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what information his Department holds on whether any British-licenced weaponry has been used by Saudi Arabia to bomb Saada province in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390917","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-28","<p>“Local spending bodies” is not a term that the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) uses. For the purposes of this answer we are therefore providing information on:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ol start="1" type="1"><li><strong>BIS partner organisations that have an office in Birmingham</strong>.</li></ol><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These bodies spend money voted to BIS and have the BIS Permanent Secretary as their ultimate accounting officer. The following such organisations have offices in Birmingham:</p><p> </p><p>· ACAS</p><p> </p><p>· Insolvency Service</p><p> </p><p>· Skills Funding Agency</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ol start="2" type="1"><li><strong>The categories of body set out in PQ UIN 7817</strong>.</li></ol><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These bodies are part of the wider delivery chain and spend money voted to BIS that is allocated to these bodies through BIS Partner Organisations rather than from BIS directly. These bodies do not have the BIS Permanent Secretary as their accounting officer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>a) Further Education colleges and b) apprenticeships providers</p><p> </p><p>Details of further education providers and other training bodies receiving public funding are published and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/378355/feandskills-learners-by-provider-local-authority-learner-characteristics-1314.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/378355/feandskills-learners-by-provider-local-authority-learner-characteristics-1314.xls</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>c) Local economic partnerships</p><p> </p><p>· The Greater Birmingham and Solihull Local Economic Partnership</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>d) Other local bodies which draw upon funds voted to his Department</p><p> </p><p>· Aston University</p><p> </p><p>· Birmingham City University</p><p> </p><p>· The University of Birmingham</p><p> </p><p>· University College Birmingham</p><p> </p><p>· Newman University</p><p> </p><p>· Energy Systems Catapult</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390917/answer",,,,,"7815 ; 7817","2015-07-28T07:45:05.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390917/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390917/answer",,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-17","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Birmingham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 16 July 2015 to Question 6219, which local spending bodies in the city of Birmingham spend money voted to his Department.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","7816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390918","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-24","<p>Statistics showing the number of English domiciled applicants awarded Maintenance Grants for study at UK providers are published annually by the Student Loans Company (SLC) in the Statistical First Release ‘<em>Student Support for Higher Education in England</em>’.</p><p><a href="http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/full-catalogue-of-official-statistics/student-support-for-higher-education-in-england.aspx" target="_blank">http://www.slc.co.uk/official-statistics/full-catalogue-of-official-statistics/student-support-for-higher-education-in-england.aspx</a></p><p>The distribution of maintenance support grants awarded to English applicants at UK providers over the last ten years has been provided in the attached table. Complete data for the academic year 2014/15 will be published by the SLC in November 2015.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390918/answer","PQ-UIN-7850-table.pdf","PQ-UIN-7850-table.pdf","Support grants awarded to English applicants table","Support grants awarded to English applicants table",,"2015-07-24T08:45:30.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390918/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390918/answer",,,,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-17","Students: Grants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many students (a) were in receipt of a full, (b) were in receipt of a partial and (c) did not receive a maintenance grant in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","7850"
