"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391019","Home Office","false","2015-08-05","<p>£157,145.18 was paid to panel members of the child abuse inquiry in the 2014-15 financial year.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391019/answer",,,,,,"2015-08-05T13:19:12.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391019/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391019/answer",,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-17","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was paid to panel members of the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse in the 2014-15 financial year.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391020","Home Office","false","2015-07-28","<p>Neither Dame Fiona Woolf nor Baroness Butler-Sloss has received any payment in relation to the independent panel inquiry into child sexual abuse.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391020/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-28T13:42:56.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391020/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391020/answer",,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-17","Child Sexual Abuse Independent Panel Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was paid to (a) Dame Fiona Woolf and (b) Baroness Butler-Sloss for their work on the Independent Inquiry into Child Sexual Abuse.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391021","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>A full statement of progress on each of the goals and targets has been published in DFID’s Annual Report and Accounts 2014 to 2015.</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391021/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:49:12.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391021/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391021/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the progress towards achieving the Millennium Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391022","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>The UK is fully committed to the global eradication of polio. The Secretary of State for International Development makes the most of opportunities to raise awareness of polio eradication efforts and, wherever appropriate, discusses polio with her international counterparts. For example, last year the Secretary of State for International Development made a key note speech at Rotary International with representatives from India, Nigeria, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Afghanistan and Indonesia, along with key polio campaigners and global health bodies.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to be a strong supporter of global polio eradication efforts. In 2013, the UK committed £300 million over six years to polio eradication, which will help vaccinate up to 360 million children. The UK actively participates in the global Polio Oversight Board, helping to ensure a strong focus on results and achieving eradication. We are very close to making polio the second human disease in history to be wiped out, and it is crucial to maintain international momentum</p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391022/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:56:21.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391022/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391022/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with her international counterparts on the eradication of polio.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","7818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391023","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>As a result of the crisis, the UN estimate that 21 million Yemenis (more than 80% of the population) are in need of humanitarian assistance. Of those, over 6 million people are facing severe shortages of food and 1.6 million women and children are suffering from acute malnutrition.</p><p> </p><p>DFID has allocated £55 million to support humanitarian response in Yemen which will provide emergency shelter, healthcare, water and food assistance, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the humanitarian response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391023/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:04:15.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391023/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391023/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of how many people are at risk of death arising from the current conflict in Yemen; and what steps she is taking to protect such people.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391024","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has forecast that Yemen’s economy will contract by 2.2% in 2015 and that Yemen’s debt has risen to over 50% of GDP. According to the World Food Programme (WFP), average wheat flour prices in July are 34% higher than their pre-crisis levels, whilst diesel prices are up 427% over the same period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DFID has allocated £55 million to support humanitarian response in Yemen which will provide emergency shelter, healthcare, water and food assistance, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the humanitarian response.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391024/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:06:21.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391024/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391024/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the economic effects of the conflict in Yemen; and what steps she is taking to help people affected by that conflict.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391025","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>DFID has allocated £55 million for humanitarian response in Yemen which is providing emergency shelter, healthcare, water and food assistance, as well as supporting UN work to co-ordinate the humanitarian response. Of that, DFID has allocated almost £40 million towards the UN 2015 Humanitarian Appeal.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Full details of all pledges to the UN Appeal can be found on the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (UNOCHA) Financial Tracking Service website (<a href="https://fts.unocha.org/pageloader.aspx?page=emerg-emergencyDetails&amp;appealID=1087" target="_blank">https://fts.unocha.org/pageloader.aspx?page=emerg-emergencyDetails&amp;appealID=1087</a>).</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391025/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:05:09.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391025/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391025/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much her Department has allocated to the UN humanitarian appeal for Yemen; and what information her Department holds on how much aid has been allocated by other countries.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391026","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>The UK is a strong supporter of global polio eradication efforts. As one of the top three donors to the Global Polio Eradication Initiative, the UK leads by example. In 2013, the UK committed £300 million over six years to polio eradication, which will help vaccinate up to 360 million children.</p><p> </p><p>The UK will continue to encourage countries to donate to the Global Polio Eradication Initiative to ensure that we have the required funding to successfully eradicate the disease before 2019. As a lead donor, the UK actively participates in the global Polio Oversight Board, helping to ensure cost-effective use of funds and a strong focus on results.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Welwyn Hatfield","Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391026/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:57:56.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391026/answer","Biography information for Grant Shapps","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391026/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Developing Countries: Poliomyelitis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to encourage other countries to donate to the Global Polio Eradication Initiative.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","7819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391027","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>We do not hold information on how many people have been displaced by coalition bombing of Sa’ada province. As of the 6 July, the UN estimates that there are just over 23,000 people displaced in Sa’ada Governorate and nearly 1.3 million people have been displaced within Yemen overall since the crisis began in March.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391027/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:08:31.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391027/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391027/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what information her Department holds on how many people have been displaced by the coalition bombing of Saada province in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391028","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-23","<p>All agencies supported by the UK are humanitarian organisations which have robust systems in place, to ensure that UK aid follows humanitarian principles and reaches those in need.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391028/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:09:24.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391028/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391028/answer",,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-17","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she is taking to ensure that donors' funds provided to UN and other non-governmental humanitarian agencies for use in Yemen will be delivered impartially to civilians in that country based on established humanitarian principles without political interference.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","7891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391029","Department of Health","false","2015-07-23","<p>On 25 March, the Prime Minister announced that £25 million would be allocated to support transition to a reformed scheme. A written ministerial statement (<a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2015-07-20/HCWS146/" target="_blank">HCWS146</a>) was given on 20 July, stating that no decision has yet been made but it will be used appropriately to support any transitional arrangements once we have consulted on how a new scheme might be structured.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391029/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T15:05:13.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391029/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391029/answer",,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-17","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what arrangements have been made to distribute the £25 million of additional compensation to people infected with contaminated blood; when he plans to report progress on this matter to the House; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","7788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391030","Prime Minister","false","2015-07-23","<p>It is a long-standing policy of the government, and previous governments going back for over half a century, to embed military personnel in a whole range of countries. I was aware that the Defence Secretary authorised the first embed with US forces in Syria in the autumn of last year.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391030/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:45:39.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391030/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391030/answer",,,,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-07-17","Syria: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when he was first informed of the involvement of British military personnel in military actions in Syria after the vote against military action in Syria on 30 August 2013.","false","Biography information for Brendan O'Hara","Argyll and Bute","Brendan O'Hara","7790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391031","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-24","<p>Throughout the independence referendum leading members of the Yes campaign repeatedly asserted that it would be a ‘once in a generation’ or a ‘once in a lifetime’ event. For example, in September 2013, Nicola Sturgeon described the independence referendum on BBC television as a ‘once in a lifetime opportunity for Scotland’ and in November 2013, the Scottish Government’s white paper, <em>Scotland’s Future: Your Guide to an Independent Scotland</em>, which was produced at taxpayers’ expense and made freely available to anyone in Scotland, called the referendum ‘a once in a generation opportunity to follow a different path’. In the context of these and other assurances, and following extensive debate, in September 2014 people in Scotland voted decisively, by a majority of over ten per cent, to reject independence and to keep our family of nations together. We await with interest the publication of the parties’ election manifestos.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391031/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T15:52:45.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391031/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391031/answer",,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-07-17","Sovereignty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policy on a further referendum on Scottish independence of the Scottish Parliament election in 2016 delivering a majority for political parties committed to the holding of such a referendum.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","7765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391032","Scotland Office","false","2015-07-24","<p>Given the clear and repeated commitments of leading Yes campaigners, not least the First Minister herself, during the independence referendum campaign that the vote was a ‘once in a generation’ or ‘once in a lifetime’ event, and given that a clear majority of Scots voted No in that referendum, my Department has not prepared contingency plans for the possibility of a further referendum being the policy of the Scottish Government after the Scottish Parliament election in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391032/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T15:54:31.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391032/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391032/answer",,,,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2015-07-17","Sovereignty: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what contingency plans his Department has prepared for the possibility of a further referendum on Scottish independence being the policy of the Scottish Government after the Scottish Parliament election in 2016.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","7766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391033","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-22","<p>Highways England keeps the strategic trunk road network under continuous review to identify places where there is a need for studies to support the case for improvements and Highways England are starting a safety study of the route this financial year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Highways England will soon initiate preparation of Route Strategies for 2020-25. These will form an integral part of the investment planning process. If potential improvements to the A595 are identified, they will be considered within the next Road Investment Strategy covering the same period.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391033/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T10:10:27.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391033/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391033/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-17","A595","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will conduct a feasibility study on improving the trunk road section of the A595.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391034","Department for Transport","false","2015-09-08","<p>There are two bee hives sited on land owned by the Department.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391034/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-08T09:39:54.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391034/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391034/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-17","Department for Transport: Bees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many bee hives are sited on land owned by his Department.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","7847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391035","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-22","<p>Total expenditure per regions is complicated to calculate as it has to include franchise cost/revenue, infrastructure cost and major project costs, many of which cross regional boundaries. In this instance, spending needs to be compared to rail usage.</p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p>The most recent government expenditure on rail is below:</p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="6"><p><strong>Government expenditure on railways<sup>1</sup> per head of population</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Region</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2009/10</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North East</p></td><td><p>£59</p></td><td><p>£58</p></td><td><p>£55</p></td><td><p>£51</p></td><td><p>£50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>North West</p></td><td><p>£97</p></td><td><p>£98</p></td><td><p>£88</p></td><td><p>£88</p></td><td><p>£85</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Yorkshire &amp; Humber</p></td><td><p>£95</p></td><td><p>£93</p></td><td><p>£102</p></td><td><p>£100</p></td><td><p>£100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East Midlands</p></td><td><p>£45</p></td><td><p>£41</p></td><td><p>£37</p></td><td><p>£38</p></td><td><p>£36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>West Midlands</p></td><td><p>£61</p></td><td><p>£53</p></td><td><p>£49</p></td><td><p>£50</p></td><td><p>£47</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>East of England</p></td><td><p>£58</p></td><td><p>£54</p></td><td><p>£59</p></td><td><p>£56</p></td><td><p>£56</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>London</p></td><td><p>£386</p></td><td><p>£369</p></td><td><p>£330</p></td><td><p>£270</p></td><td><p>£298</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South East</p></td><td><p>£85</p></td><td><p>£82</p></td><td><p>£69</p></td><td><p>£68</p></td><td><p>£66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South West</p></td><td><p>£49</p></td><td><p>£46</p></td><td><p>£41</p></td><td><p>£42</p></td><td><p>£39</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£120</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£115</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£106</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£96</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£99</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p>1 Includes expenditure on all types of railway</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td><p>Source: HMT, ONS</p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p><em></em></p><p> </p><p><em></em></p><p>The above table shows estimated government expenditure on railways per head of population in each region of England between 2009/10 and 2013/14, the latest year for which figures are available.</p><p><em></em></p><p> </p><p><em></em></p><p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p /><p /> <p> </p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391035/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T10:05:12.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391035/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391035/answer",,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-17","Railways: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been spent on rail services per head of population in each region of England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391036","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-22","<p /> <p>Following the consultation <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/strengthening-families-promoting-parental-responsibility-the-future-of-child-maintenance" target="_blank">‘Strengthening families, promoting parental responsibility: the future of child maintenance’</a>, and debates in both Houses, the level of the application fee was reduced from £100 to £20. The fee is intended to strike the right balance of ensuring parents do not default into the statutory scheme, without placing an unreasonable financial burden on those who are unable to reach a family based arrangement. It also provides a nominal contribution to a system that is expensive to administer.</p><p> </p><p>Application fees do not apply to victims of domestic violence or to applicants aged 18 or under.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391036/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T13:02:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391036/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391036/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what factors were taken into account in setting the application fee for the Child Maintenance Service at £20.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391037","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The Department for Work and Pensions is currently analysing the first four waves of the new Understanding Society survey in order to produce an updated Low Income Dynamics publication. We will pre-announce the timing of the publication in line with National Statistics Codes of Practice at the appropriate stage in this analysis.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391037/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T16:35:04.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391037/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391037/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Low Incomes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he intends to publish the next edition of the Low Income Dynamics analysis.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7837"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391038","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-21","<p /> <p>The Government does not produce child poverty statistics at local authority or parliamentary constituency level.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391038/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T10:23:45.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391038/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391038/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of children living in poverty in (a) Copeland and (b) Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391039","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-22","<p /> <p>Information on the number of Work Programme referrals, attachments and job outcomes to March 2015 by various geographies, including parliamentary constituencies, is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/WorkProg/tabtool.html</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dwp-tabulation-tool-guidance</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391039/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T11:22:24.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391039/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391039/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Work Programme: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Copeland constituency participated in the Work Programme scheme in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391040","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-23","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391040/answer","PQ7881 UKSA reply.pdf","PQ7881 UKSA reply.pdf","UK Statistics Reply ","UK Statistics Reply ",,"2015-07-23T10:11:45.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391040/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391040/answer",,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-17","Zero Hours Contracts: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people are employed on zero hours contracts in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391041","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-21","<p /> <p>To prevent young people slipping straight into a life on benefits, from April 2017 the Government will remove the automatic entitlement to housing support for new claims in Universal Credit from 18-21 year olds who are out of work. This will ensure young people in the benefits system face the same choices as young people who work and who may not be able to afford to leave home.</p><p> </p><p>We will ensure that vulnerable young people who are in need of support for their housing needs continue to receive it. Government will consider the impact in line with our legal obligations as part of that process.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391041/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T12:45:06.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391041/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391041/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the Government's policy is on 18 to 21 year olds in need of housing support.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391042","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-09-07","<p /> <p>The Department’s current policy is that calls to claim benefit by telephone should be free to a customer so it uses 0800 free phone numbers where these calls typically take longer. The current Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) policy is that all calls should be free to our 0800 numbers to claim:</p><p> </p><p>· State Pension;</p><p>· Pension Credit;</p><p>· Jobseeker’s Allowance;</p><p>· Income Support;</p><p>· Employment Support Allowance; and,</p><p>· Personal Independence Payment</p><p> </p><p>It is free to call DWP 0800 numbers from all major landline providers. DWP has secured agreements to ensure that it is free to call via six of the UK’s largest mobile phone operators.</p><p> </p><p>For other enquiry helplines the Department has now introduced 0345 numbers and has started the process to cease offering 0845 number options from 1 July. Any charges that apply to these calls will be set by the customer’s telephone or mobile operator and vary depending on call plan type and the time of day at which the call is made.</p><p> </p><p>Calls to 0345 numbers cost no more than a standard geographic call, and count towards any free or inclusive minutes in your landline or mobile phone contract. DWP does not use premium rate numbers.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391042/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:37:27.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391042/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/391042/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many higher-rate telephone numbers his Department operates for new and existing claimants, and for which benefit categories; and what the average cost and duration is of each call to each of those numbers by benefit category.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7892"
