"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390689","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>Updated guidance and advice will be available on tax credits entitlement in advance of the implementation of the new measures, announced in the Summer Budget 2015.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390689/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:01:51.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390689/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390689/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what guidance his Department has issued on how tax credit claimants can calculate how much their tax credit entitlement will change as a result of changes to tax credit entitlement announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","7590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390690","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-23","<p>The government has sought to make private investment in infrastructure more attractive through a number of initiatives.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government established the UK Guarantees Scheme (UKGS) in 2012 to help infrastructure projects access capital market finance by enabling them to issue government-backed bonds. A total of £1.7bn has been guaranteed to date, supporting 7 projects with a combined capital value of approximately £4bn.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Platforms such as the Insurers’ Infrastructure Investment Forum and the Pensions Infrastructure Platform have been set up to maximise institutional investment in infrastructure. In 2013, a group of six insurers agreed to aim to invest £25bn in UK infrastructure over 5 years – with over £5bn already invested they are on track to meet this goal.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government’s efforts to attract private investment in infrastructure were recognised in Nabarro LLP’s Infrastructure Index, which assessed the UK as number one in the world for attracting investment in infrastructure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The UK’s National Infrastructure Plan is underpinned by a pipeline of projects worth £411 billion to 2020 and beyond. 64% of these projects are funded solely by the private sector. Further information can be found in the government’s updated national infrastructure pipeline, which was published this month.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390690/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T14:55:06.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390690/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390690/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Infrastructure: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to improve the UK's attractiveness to private investment in infrastructure; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390691","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Government is making changes to Tax Credits and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMT has published distributional analysis information on the impact of the Summer Budget 2015 tax credit measures on households. This information can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443229/PU1822_Distributional_Analysis.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443229/PU1822_Distributional_Analysis.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government is focusing the tax credits system on those who need it most. Prior to 2010, 9 out of 10 families with children in the UK were eligible for tax credits The measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015 will result in 5 out of 10 UK families being eligible for tax credits support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of affected households and total reduction in credits to households in Scotland is not available.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes information on families’ tax credit award within Scotland. The most recent available data is for 2013-14 and can be found here on gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390691/answer",,,,,"7652 ; 7732","2015-07-21T15:59:59.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390691/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390691/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Welfare Tax Credits: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an estimate of the total reduction in credits to households in Scotland that will arise in the next financial year as a result of measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","7595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390692","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage on local authority finances will be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures on local authorities. The Department has regular discussions with the Local Government Association about a range of matters, and will continue to engage with them and other interested parties as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390692/answer",,,,,"7739 ; 7740","2015-07-21T14:27:55.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390692/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390692/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will estimate what the cost to each local authority in England and Wales will be of paying staff the new National Living Wage in April (a) 2016 and (b) 2020.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","7737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390693","Department of Health","false","2015-07-21","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage on local authority finances will be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures on local authorities.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390693/answer",,,,,"7741","2015-07-21T12:22:06.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390693/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390693/answer",,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-16","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what research his Department has commissioned on the effect on local authority budgets of paying the new National Living Wage to external staff commissioned by local authorities to provide adult social care.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","7738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390694","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The reforms to Child Tax Credit and Housing Benefit will ensure that in the future, families on benefits will have to make the same financial decisions as families supporting themselves through work.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390694/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:06:41.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390694/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390694/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of proposed changes to tax credits and housing benefit in the Summer Budget 2015 on long-term trends in family size.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","7688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390695","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Government is making changes to Tax Credits and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMT has published distributional analysis information on the impact of the Summer Budget 2015 tax credit measures on households. This information can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443229/PU1822_Distributional_Analysis.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/443229/PU1822_Distributional_Analysis.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government is focusing the tax credits system on those who need it most. Prior to 2010, 9 out of 10 families with children in the UK were eligible for tax credits The measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015 will result in 5 out of 10 UK families being eligible for tax credits support.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The number of affected households and total reduction in credits to households in Scotland is not available.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes information on families’ tax credit award within Scotland. The most recent available data is for 2013-14 and can be found here on gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390695/answer",,,,,"7595 ; 7652","2015-07-21T15:59:59.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390695/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390695/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the average change in income for (a) women and (b) households with children of the tax credit changes outlined in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","7732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390696","HM Treasury","false","2015-09-07","<p>The Government has introduced a range of measures to support savers, including increasing the ISA limit to £15,240, and making ISAs simpler by allowing that money to be held in a cash ISA, a stocks and shares ISA, or split in any combination between the two. The ISA allows individuals to save for a wide variety of purposes, including funeral payments.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390696/answer",,,,,,"2015-09-07T15:19:37.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390696/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390696/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Individual Savings Accounts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will establish a tax-free savings vehicle specifically designed to save for funerals.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","7682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390697","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is legally prohibited from discussing the tax affairs of identifiable businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 18 of the Commissioners for Revenue &amp; Customs Act 2005 imposes a duty of confidentiality upon officers of HMRC which means they are unable to disclose information which relates to functions of HMRC.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, please let me assure you that HMRC is fully committed to ensuring that everyone pays the tax that is due.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390697/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:23:34.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390697/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390697/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Covent Garden Market Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what payments have accrued to the Exchequer from the New Covent Garden Market Authority in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390698","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>HM Treasury regularly reviews and deploys its staff as appropriate to meet ministerial and departmental priorities. Appropriate resource is being allocated to work on the Scottish rate of income tax from within existing departmental budgets.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390698/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:13:32.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390698/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390698/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Income Tax: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many officials in his Department are working on the Scottish rate of income tax.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","7754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390699","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-24","<p>This information requested is published in HM Revenue and Custom (HMRC) National Statistics table PEN6, available on GOV.UK: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/registered-pension-schemes-cost-of-tax-relief <br></p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390699/answer",,,,,"7180","2015-07-24T12:07:19.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390699/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390699/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much tax relief was granted (a) to higher rate taxpayers and (b) in total in respect of (i) defined contribution and (ii) defined benefit pension schemes in 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","7717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390700","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage on local authority finances will be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures on local authorities. The Department has regular discussions with the Local Government Association about a range of matters, and will continue to engage with them and other interested parties as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390700/answer",,,,,"7737 ; 7740","2015-07-21T14:27:55.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390700/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390700/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what research his Department has carried out on the effect of the National Living Wage on local authority staffing costs; and if he will place a copy of such research in the Library.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","7739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390701","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-21","<p>The policy which limits the child element in tax credits and Universal Credit to two children, will only apply to those families with children born on or after 6 April 2017 or those making a new claim to Universal Credit after April 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government will work closely with stakeholders on the details of implementation.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390701/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:58:06.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390701/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390701/answer",,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-07-16","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to Paragraph 2.103 of the Summer Budget 2015, if he will estimate the number of women who will be affected by the limit of child tax credits; and how many such women will be covered by exceptional circumstances.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","7734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390702","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage on local authority finances will be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures on local authorities. The Department has regular discussions with the Local Government Association about a range of matters, and will continue to engage with them and other interested parties as part of the Spending Review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390702/answer",,,,,"7737 ; 7739","2015-07-21T14:27:55.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390702/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390702/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Local Government: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with the Local Government Association on providing financial support for local authorities to assist meeting any costs of paying staff the National Living Wage.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","7740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390703","Department of Health","false","2015-07-21","<p>The impact of the new National Living Wage on local authority finances will be considered during the Spending Review as part of an overall assessment of spending pressures on local authorities.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390703/answer",,,,,"7738","2015-07-21T12:22:06.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390703/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390703/answer",,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-16","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of paying the National Living Wage for adult social care commissioned by local authorities over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","7741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390704","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-22","<p>Our proposal is to grant permission in principle for identified sites in a new statutory brownfield register to move towards a zonal system similar to that seen in other countries. Further details on how the measure will work will be made available in the autumn.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390704/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T15:53:40.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390704/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390704/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.15 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, if he will issue guidance on the term zonal system, used in connection with brownfield sites; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390705","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the Written Ministerial Statement of 21 July 2015, HCWS 172.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390705/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T16:43:21.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390705/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390705/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.10 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, how much time his Department will allow local authorities to put in place local plans where they have not yet done so before his Department will intervene to enforce this.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390706","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>There are many factors which can influence rates of house building. My Department keeps these issues under review. This Government’s stewardship of the economy has helped to keep interest rates at a record low, helping many families with their mortgages.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390706/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:23:01.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390706/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390706/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he has made an assessment of the potential effect of a rise in mortgage rates on future levels of house building.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390707","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-23","<p>Our Ministerial Statement of 21 July, HCWS172, sets out our commitment to accelerate Local Plan production. We are clear that any intervention will not compromise effective comunity engagement.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390707/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T15:49:30.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390707/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390707/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.10 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, what steps he plans to take to ensure that there is adequate consultation with local people when imposing local plans on behalf of local authorities.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390708","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>The detail of how the policy will be implemented will be determined following successful EU treaty negotiation. However, local authorities are already experienced in assessing whether foreign national applicants meet the eligibility criteria for social housing set by central government as well as the authority’s local residency test.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390708/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:30:51.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390708/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390708/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2015 to Question 5575, how the four-year residency of EU migrants is to be proven; upon whom the onus of proof that the residency criterion is met will lie; and what measures social housing providers will take to verify any proof they are given that residency criteria are met.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","7747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390709","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>In developing the detail of our proposals we will work with the Mayor of London, who has the strategic planning responsibility for London including for infrastructure plans. This will include consideration of what type of buildings should benefit from the new rights, and any necessary requirements to protect local amenity and address any impacts.<br><br>All developments benefiting from the new rights will still need to comply with current building regulations, as well any other relevant legislation such as the Party Wall Act and environmental legislation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390709/answer",,,,,"7720 ; 7721 ; 7756","2015-07-21T15:06:34.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390709/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390709/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.21 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, whether height restrictions will apply in the policy to remove the need for planning permission for upwards extensions.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390710","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>This Government reaffirmed in its election manifesto that we would maintain strong protection for Green Belt in line with our policy in the National Planning Policy Framework. The Framework makes clear that most new building is inappropriate in Green Belt, and that a Green Belt boundary may be altered only in exceptional circumstances, through the Local Plan. Planning guidance reminds local authorities that, in planning to meet housing need, they must have regard to policies in the Framework on the protection of areas such as Green Belt, which indicate that development should be restricted. Where there is no up-to-date Local Plan, new draft Plans will continue to be produced in consultation with local people.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390710/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:49:36.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390710/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390710/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 917 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, whether under these proposals local authorities could be required to allow new building on greenbelt sites in cases where the Government imposes a local plan on their behalf.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390711","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-22","<p>During the last Parliament we undertook a high level consultation on speeding up Section 106 negotiations, which concluded that these can be a significant delay in processing planning applications, impacting on the delivery of much needed housing and local economic growth. Building on consultation responses, we are developing a dispute resolution process to speed up the determining of planning applications enabling development to be built more quickly.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390711/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T15:56:11.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390711/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390711/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.17 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, how he will implement a dispute resolution mechanism for section 106 agreements.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390712","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>Most planning decisions are already made on time - 77% of major decisions in 2014-15. It is important for every council to give planning the priority it needs, as effective planning supports growth and revenue for the area. The resources available to local government as a whole will be considered as part of this autumn's spending review.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390712/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:52:22.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390712/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390712/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.17 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, how he plans to adequately resource local authorities to ensure planning decisions are made on time where they are currently failing to do so.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390713","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>In developing the detail of our proposals we will work with the Mayor of London, who has the strategic planning responsibility for London including for infrastructure plans. This will include consideration of what type of buildings should benefit from the new rights, and any necessary requirements to protect local amenity and address any impacts.<br><br>All developments benefiting from the new rights will still need to comply with current building regulations, as well any other relevant legislation such as the Party Wall Act and environmental legislation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390713/answer",,,,,"7721 ; 7722 ; 7756","2015-07-21T15:06:34.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390713/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390713/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.21 of the document Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, what assessment his Department has made of additional infrastructure needs as a result of removing the need for planning permission for upwards extensions.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390714","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>In developing the detail of our proposals we will work with the Mayor of London, who has the strategic planning responsibility for London including for infrastructure plans. This will include consideration of what type of buildings should benefit from the new rights, and any necessary requirements to protect local amenity and address any impacts.<br><br>All developments benefiting from the new rights will still need to comply with current building regulations, as well any other relevant legislation such as the Party Wall Act and environmental legislation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390714/answer",,,,,"7720 ; 7721 ; 7722","2015-07-21T15:06:33.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390714/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390714/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 921 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of removing the need for planning permission for upwards extensions on building safety.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390715","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>In developing the detail of our proposals we will work with the Mayor of London, who has the strategic planning responsibility for London including for infrastructure plans. This will include consideration of what type of buildings should benefit from the new rights, and any necessary requirements to protect local amenity and address any impacts.<br><br>All developments benefiting from the new rights will still need to comply with current building regulations, as well any other relevant legislation such as the Party Wall Act and environmental legislation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390715/answer",,,,,"7720 ; 7722 ; 7756","2015-07-21T15:06:34.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390715/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390715/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.21 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, whether the policy of allowing extra storeys to be built on neighbouring properties in London will apply to (a) residential and (b) commercial property.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390716","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>We are committed to allowing nationally significant infrastructure projects with an element of housing to be consented under the Planning Act 2008. This will require amendments to primary legislation and information on the scope of the proposal will be set out in a future Bill.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390716/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:40:06.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390716/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390716/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 917 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, what the scope is of those projects with an element of housing development which can be fast tracked through the Nationally Significant Infrastructure Projects regime.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390717","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>Statistics on additional affordable housing provided in each local authority area in England are published in the Department’s live tables 1006 (social rent), and 1006a (affordable rent), which are available at the following link:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-affordable-housing-supply</p><p> </p><p>These figures include both newly built housing and acquisitions.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390717/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:33:31.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390717/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390717/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) social and (b) affordable homes were built in (i) London and (ii) each London borough in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","7671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390718","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>Our planning guidance includes a strong focus on design, and provides advice on tools such as design codes. Our technical guidance on householder permitted development rights sets out advice on minimising the visual impacts of loft extensions.<br><br><em><br></em></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390718/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:34:00.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390718/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390718/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Building Alterations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what guidance his Department has issued to local authorities on the aesthetic effect of loft extensions on residential areas.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390719","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>According to the English Housing Survey, in 2010 there were 434,000 children and 708,000 adults living in overcrowded accommodation in London. For 2011, there were 435,000 children and 703,000 adults, and for 2012 there were 420,000 children and 693,000 adults living in overcrowded accomodation in London.<br><br>My Department does not record or collect the information requested at London borough level.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390719/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:26:48.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390719/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390719/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Overcrowding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) children and (b) adults were living in overcrowded accommodation in (i) London and (ii) each London borough in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","7674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390720","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-21","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given on 18 March 2015 to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-03-12/227440/" target="_blank">227440</a>.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390720/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T10:08:46.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390720/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390720/answer",,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-16","Social Rented Housing: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the reduction in rent payment rates amongst social sector tenants upon moving to a direct payment scheme.","false","Biography information for Mr Mark Prisk","Hertford and Stortford","Mr Mark Prisk","7675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390721","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>An estimate of the amount of development on Green Belt land in the year 2011 was published in the Department’s Land Use Change Statistics in 2013:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/land-use-change-statistics-in-england-2011" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/land-use-change-statistics-in-england-2011</a></p><p> </p><p>Land Use Change Statistics for the year 2013-14, produced using a new and better methodology that will allow more detailed statistical and spatial analysis will be published on 6 August.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390721/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:03:57.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390721/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390721/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Green Belt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the level of building on greenbelt sites in each year since 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390722","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-22","<p>The Government makes no assessment of this issue, it is the operation of the free market.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390722/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T15:31:29.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390722/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390722/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the effects on housing supply and affordability of the practice of investors selling on a house at a higher price to another investor immediately after purchase; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390723","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","My rt. hon. Friend, the Secretary of State's letter of 14 July 2014 sets out the weightings he gave in his determination of this appeal. The letter is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/recovered-appeal-former-aerodrome-north-orbital-road-upper-colne-valley-hertfordshire-ref-2109433-14-july-2014.","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390723/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:28:18.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390723/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390723/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Railways: Radlett","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what weight he gave to the likely effect on commuter train services of the work needed to the Elstree Tunnels when approving the Radlett Rail Freight Terminal.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","7545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390724","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-07-24","<p>The competition will establish a demonstrator in a &quot;city region&quot; which can include less densely-populated areas and solutions will not necessarily all be based in the central urban area. The competition will also establish internet of things applications and solutions which are at scale and replicable in other areas.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390724/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T12:00:33.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390724/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390724/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","Internet: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will extend the Internet of Things competition for UK cities launched on 13 July 2015 to rural communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390725","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-07-24","<p>Arts Council England works closely with stakeholders to engage young people in rural areas. Working with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs the Arts Council undertook a data and evidence review to identify strengths and challenges of the arts sector in rural England. Key findings from the report published in March 2015 were:</p><p> </p><p>· People living in rural areas are more likely to be engaged with the arts than those living in urban areas (Taking Part Survey*)</p><p>· 19% of Grants for the Arts** activity; and 35% of National Portfolio Organisation*** touring in 2012/13 reached rural communities</p><p>· Applicants from rural areas made 13% of individual Grants for the Arts applications and 14% of organisational applications in the 2.5 years to August 2014.</p><p> </p><p>*The Taking Part survey collects data on many aspects of leisure, culture and sport in England, as well as an in-depth range of socio-demographic information on respondents. In respect of the Arts, data is collected about the reasons for participating and not participating, barriers to participation, and the frequency of participation are also collected.</p><p>** Grants for the arts is the Arts Council's Lottery-funded grant programme for individuals, arts organisations and other people who use the arts in their work. Grants are available for activities carried out over a set period and which engage people in England in arts activities and help artists and arts organisations in England carry out their work.</p><p> </p><p>***National Portfolio Organisations receive regular funding directly from the Arts Council.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390725/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T12:03:26.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390725/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390725/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","Arts: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to encourage more young people in rural communities to pursue careers in the arts.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390726","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-07-24","<p>The UK City of Culture competition is open to areas that have a clear urban focus, which could include a city or large town, two or more neighbouring cities or towns, or a closely linked set of urban areas. While the Government has no plans to introduce a UK Community of Culture award, we recognise the importance of culture in rural communities: how it can impact on health, social cohesion and personal development, as well generating tourism, jobs, and wealth.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390726/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T11:59:34.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390726/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390726/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","UK City of Culture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will introduce a UK Community of Culture Award to allow non-cities to experience the same benefits as cities awarded UK City of Culture awards.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390727","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-10-01","<p>The Government, through Sport England is investing £20 million in the Amateur Swimming Association and other partners between 2013-17 to get more people swimming in England.</p><p>Sport England also invests in facilities such as pools and changing rooms, including £388,797 in four such projects in Cumbria since 2012.</p><p>The Government has provided over £300m of cross-government ring-fenced funding for academic years 2013/14 and 2014/15, to improve PE and sport. This is the only curriculum subject with ring-fenced funding.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the new national curriculum, which came into force from September 2014, swimming and water safety remain compulsory in the programme of study for physical education (PE) at primary level.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390727/answer",,,,,,"2015-10-01T15:09:08.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390727/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390727/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","Swimming: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of (a) children and (b) adults in Cumbria who swim.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390728","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-07-28","<p>Since 2012, Sport England has invested over £64 million of Lottery and Grant-in-Aid funding in projects in the North West to get more people playing sport. <br> <br> Sport England’s Satellite Club programme brings community sport clubs into schools and colleges. In the North West over 1,000 Satellite Clubs have been set up, getting more than 46,000 young people playing sport.<br> <br> Sportivate is Sport England’s Olympic and Paralympic Legacy programme which introduces young people to sport through a six week coaching course. In the North West, there have been over 5,000 projects with 77,000 young people completing their Sportivate course.<br> <br> The delivery of London 2012 showed that the UK can successfully hold the biggest sporting events and has helped attract more major events to this country. Manchester is one of the most significant current hubs of major events activity in the UK – along with London and Glasgow. In the period 2013-19, a total of 9 UK Sport-supported major events have either been held or secured for the city, with around £1.4m of UK Sport investment generating an estimated £3.3m of economic impact. <br> <br> The meta-evaluation of the impacts of London 2012, carried out for DCMS by an independent consortium led by Grant Thornton and published in July 2013, estimated that the net economic benefits to the North West region related to London 2012 over the period 2004 to 2020 would be between £1.77bn and £2.46bn (Gross Value Added at 2009 prices).<br> <br> <br></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390728/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-28T16:36:12.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390728/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390728/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","Olympic Games 2012: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to promote the legacy of the 2012 London Olympic and Paralympic Games in the North West.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390729","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2015-07-23","<p>Advertising online is already subject to t​he UK Code of Non-broadcast Advertising, Sales Promotion and Direct Marketing ​which is administered robustly by theAdvertising Standards Authority (ASA)​.</p><p>The rules (​​which apply across media) require that online ads do not contain anything that is likely to be misleading, harmful or offensive and that they​ a​re prepared in a socially responsible way.​ ​The rules place a particular emphasis on protecting children from inappropriate or harmful content.</p><p> </p><p>The ASA’s online remit covers paid for search results, pop-up​s​, banner ads​ ​as well as (since March 2011)​ ​extending to cover marketing claims that appear on websites.The Code also applies to marketing ​on​ social media such as via Twitter,​ ​YouTube or on Facebook pages.</p><p> </p><p>There are no rules regulating the length or frequency of internet advertising and the ASA and the Committee of Advertising Practice do not have plans to introduce any​.​</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390729/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T16:48:30.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390729/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390729/answer",,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-16","Internet: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, whether regulations are in place on the length and frequency of internet advertising; and whether Ofcom or his Department has had discussions with the Advertising Standards Authority on the regulation of such advertising.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","7668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390730","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>The number of serving members of the Fleet Air Arm who have given notice of their intention to leave before serving the time that they signed up for in each of the last five years is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Years</p></td><td><p>Total No*.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2010 - June 2011</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2011 - June 2012</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2012 - June 2013</p></td><td><p>270</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2013 - June 2014</p></td><td><p>340</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2014 - June 2015</p></td><td><p>320</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*The above figures have been rounded in accordance with Defence Statistics Policy; as a result, the totals may not equal the sum of their component parts.</p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390730/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:39:32.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390730/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390730/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Air Force","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many serving members of the Fleet Air Arm have given notice of their intention to leave before serving the time that they signed up for in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","7605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390731","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>Although the Ministry of Defence does not measure the level of morale amongst Armed Forces personnel specifically on the front line, we do conduct an annual continuous attitude survey which measures morale and I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 3 June 2015 to Question 498 to the hon. Member for North Durham (Kevan Jones).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390731/answer","Hansard Extract 3 June 2015.doc","Hansard Extract 3 June 2015.doc","Armed Forces: Job Satisfaction","Armed Forces: Job Satisfaction",,"2015-07-21T15:36:09.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390731/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390731/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Armed Forces: Job Satisfaction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent assessment he has made of the level of morale amongst military personnel on the front line.","false","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","7606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390732","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-23","<p>The total number of migrants rescued each week by HMS BULWARK since she commenced search and rescue operations in the Mediterranean in May 2015 are:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Week commencing</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Migrants rescued</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>04-May 2015</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>11-May 2015</p></td><td><p>617</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>18-May 2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>25-May 2015</p></td><td><p>739</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>01-June 2015</p></td><td><p>1,449</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>08-June 2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>15-June 2015</p></td><td><p>915</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>22-June 2015</p></td><td><p>927</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>29-June 2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>4,747</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The figure of 4,747 corrects the figure of 4,752 given in the answer I gave on 13 July 2015 to Question 6011 to the hon. Member for Kettering (Philip Hollobone). This was due to a counting error.</p><p>HMS ENTERPRISE has not rescued any migrants since deploying to the Mediterranean to support the Common Security Defence Policy operation EUNAVFOR Med.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390732/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T15:45:35.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390732/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390732/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many migrants his Department has rescued from the Mediterranean sea each week since (a) HMS Bulwark and (b) HMS Enterprise commenced operations in that area.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","7650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390733","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>In June 2015 a contract was awarded to Raytheon Systems Ltd for the replenishment of Paveway IV Precision Guided Bombs.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390733/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:04:55.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390733/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390733/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Raytheon: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether the recent contract awarded to Raytheon Systems Ltd for Paveway IV bombs is intended to (a) replenish or (b) increase stock.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390734","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>We do not routinely reveal the exact numbers of precision guided weapons being provided to the Saudi authorities as to do so would prejudice commercial interests, and also to protect Saudi operational security. The release of this information would be a matter for the Saudi authorities.</p><p>The UK aims to operate one of the most rigorous and transparent export control regimes in the world. Each licence application is rigorously assessed using internationally recognised criteria. The Saudis have provided repeated assurances to us that they will be used in compliance with international humanitarian law and we continue to engage with them on those assurances.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390734/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:30:16.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390734/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390734/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2015 to Question HL1125 on Saudi Arabia: Yemen, how many precision-guided weapons of what type are being provided to Saudi Arabian armed forces; what procedures are in place to monitor the use of such weapons by Saudi Arabian armed forces; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","7584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390735","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-23","<p>This Government is committed to a 1% increase above inflation in the equipment budget until the end of this Parliament, investing over £160 billion in the next decade. This includes investing in new joint strike fighter jets, surveillance aircraft, hunter killer submarines, two aircraft carriers and the most advanced armoured vehicles. The Ministry of Defence also invests over £400 million annually in research to access cutting-edge technologies.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390735/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:42:38.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390735/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390735/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Defence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to develop the UK's technological edge in military capabilities; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390736","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-23","<p>Information on intramural and extramural expenditure for financial years (FY) between 2010-11 to 2013-14 (inclusive of non-recoverable VAT at current prices) is shown below. Expenditure for financial year 2014-15 is currently being compiled and will be available later this year following clearance by the Office of National Statistics.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Research</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2010-11</strong></p><p><strong>(£ million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2011-12</strong></p><p><strong>(£ million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2012-13</strong></p><p><strong>(£ million)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>FY 2013-14</strong></p><p><strong>(£million)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gross Expenditure on Research</p></td><td><p><strong>575</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>553</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>565</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>586</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Of which: Intramural</p></td><td><p>163</p></td><td><p>106</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>111</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Extramural</p></td><td><p>412</p></td><td><p>447</p></td><td><p>464</p></td><td><p>475</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Receipts</p></td><td><p><strong>41</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Allocated: Intramurally</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Extramurally</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>MOD expenditure on Research</p></td><td><p><strong>534</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>553</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>565</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>586</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390736/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T13:42:12.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390736/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390736/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Research: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much his Department spent on (a) intermural and (b) extramural research in each financial year between 2010-11 and 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390737","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-24","<p>The Government keeps its assessments of Russian naval, air, ground and nuclear forces under appropriate review. Further details cannot be provided in the interests of national and international security.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390737/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-24T11:12:49.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390737/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390737/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Russia: NATO","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the balance between NATO and Russian (a) naval, (b) air, (c) ground and (d) nuclear forces; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390738","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>The UK provides routine teams of personnel to support Saudi Arabia, under existing government-to-government arrangements. None of these personnel are participating directly in Saudi military operations. We currently have:</p><p>11 personnel providing mentoring and advice to the Saudi Arabian National Guard, as part of the British Military Mission to the Saudi Arabian National Guard.</p><p>18 military and 19 civilian personnel working on the Saudi Arabia National Guard Communications Project to acquire and support, modern communications capabilities for the Saudi Arabian National Guard.</p><p>76 military and 42 civilian personnel working on the Ministry of Defence Saudi Armed Forces Projects, supporting the United Kingdom's commitment to the defence of Saudi Arabia through the supply of modern military aircraft, naval vessels, weapons and associated support services to the Saudi Armed Forces.</p><p>In addition to these personnel, we have also deployed a small number of liaison personnel in Saudi and coalition Air and Maritime Headquarters. This includes personnel in the Maritime Coalition Coordination Centre in Bahrain to help ease the flow of humanitarian aid into Yemen.</p><p>We have received assurances from the Saudis that they are complying with International Humanitarian Law and we continue to engage with them on those assurances.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390738/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:33:37.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390738/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390738/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Yemen: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 9 September to Question 207819 on Saudi Arabia, what roles British personnel stationed in Saudi Arabia are carrying out in support of the Saudi armed forces military operations in Yemen; what steps he has taken to ensure that such military operations are not in breech of international humanitarian law; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","7583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390739","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-07-21","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer I gave on 23 June 2015 to Question 2510 to the right hon. Member of Mid Sussex (Sir Nicholas Soames).</p><p>We do not disclose all details of ongoing operations, including their duration, as disclosure would, or would be likely to prejudice the capability, effectiveness or security of the Armed Forces. On top of this, the duration of some operations is open-ended or subject to review.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390739/answer","Hansard Extract 23 June 2015.doc","Hansard Extract 23 June 2015.doc","Armed Forces: Deployment","Armed Forces: Deployment",,"2015-07-21T15:35:18.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390739/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390739/answer",,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-07-16","Armed Forces: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will list the 21 concurrent operations in which UK armed forces are presently engaged, together with (a) their location, (b) their planned duration and (c) the numbers of personnel involved in each such operation.","false","Biography information for Dr Julian Lewis","New Forest East","Dr Julian Lewis","7746"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390740","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>This is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the Hon Member with the information requested. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390740/answer",,,,,"7575 ; 7576 ; 7577 ; 7578","2015-07-21T09:40:47.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390740/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390740/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Runaway Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 23 of the Ofsted report, Children looked after placements by English authorities, published on 14 July 2015, how many of the 29 Chinese children who were missing from care on 31 March 2014 had gone missing from (a) foster care, (b) children's homes, (c) independent living, (d) secure units, young offenders' institutions or prisons and (e) residential schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","7574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390741","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>This is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the Hon Member with the information requested. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390741/answer",,,,,"7574 ; 7576 ; 7577 ; 7578","2015-07-21T09:40:47.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390741/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390741/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Runaway Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 23 of the Ofsted report, Children looked after placements by English authorities, published on 14 July 2015, in the care of which local authorities were the 33 children missing for six months or longer on 31 March 2014.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","7575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390742","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>This is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the Hon Member with the information requested. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390742/answer",,,,,"7574 ; 7575 ; 7577 ; 7578","2015-07-21T09:40:48.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390742/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390742/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Runaway Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 23 of the Ofsted report, Children looked after placements by English authorities, published on 14 July 2015, how many of the 33 children missing for six months or longer on 31 March 2014 were (a) male and (b) female; and how many such children were (i) under 10, (ii) aged between 10 and 12, (iii) aged between 13 and 15 and (iv) aged between 16 and 18 years old when they went missing.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","7576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390743","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>This is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the Hon Member with the information requested. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390743/answer",,,,,"7574 ; 7575 ; 7576 ; 7578","2015-07-21T09:40:48.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390743/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390743/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Runaway Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 23 of the Ofsted report, Children looked after placements by English authorities, published on 14 July 2015, how many of the 29 Chinese children who were missing from care on 31 March 2014 had been missing for (a) less than six months, (b) between six months and one year and (c) more than one year.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","7577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390744","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>This is a matter for Ofsted. I have asked Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw, to write to the Hon Member with the information requested. A copy of his reply will be placed in the House library.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390744/answer",,,,,"7574 ; 7575 ; 7576 ; 7577","2015-07-21T09:40:48.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390744/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390744/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Runaway Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 23 of the Ofsted report, Children looked after placements by English authorities, published on 14 July 2015, how many of the 33 children were missing from (a) foster care, (b) children's homes, (c) independent living, (d) secure units, young offenders' institutions or prisons and (e) residential schools.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","7578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390745","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The national curriculum sets out the essential skills and knowledge that children must be taught at school. Schools have the freedom to teach subjects or topics beyond the national curriculum to ensure that their pupils receive a rounded education.</p><p> </p><p>Using technology safely is covered at each key stage in the computing curriculum, which is compulsory for all pupils aged 5-16 in maintained schools.</p><p> </p><p>The programmes of study for the national curriculum in computing are published online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-computing-programmes-of-study/national-curriculum-in-england-computing-programmes-of-study" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-curriculum-in-england-computing-programmes-of-study/national-curriculum-in-england-computing-programmes-of-study</a></p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390745/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T09:52:31.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390745/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390745/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Schools: VDUs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will introduce lessons on managing the risk of injuries related to digital screen use to school curriculums.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390746","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The Department for Education is not aware of any legal cases that have been brought, or are in the process of being brought, against schools in the UK in relation to injuries caused by digital screen use.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390746/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T09:45:45.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390746/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390746/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Schools: VDUs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many legal cases are being brought against schools in the UK related to injuries caused by digital screen use.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390747","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The Department for Education does not hold information on absences resulting from musculoskeletal injury.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390747/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T10:10:02.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390747/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390747/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many days of absence were reported to her Department on grounds of musculoskeletal injury in the (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14 and (c) 2014-15 school year.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390748","Department for Education","false","2015-07-22","<p>There has been no specific research undertaken by the department on the potential effect of digital screen use on students in the last five years.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390748/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T11:47:41.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390748/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390748/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Students: VDUs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what research her Department has undertaken on the potential effect of digital screen use on students in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390749","Department for Education","false","2015-07-22","<p>The Secretary of State has not met with any civil society groups to discuss the potential adverse health effects of introducing more technology in schools.</p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390749/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-22T11:49:01.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390749/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390749/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Schools: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent meetings she has had with civil society groups on potential adverse health effects of introducing more technology in schools.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390750","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Department for Education does not provide schools with dedicated funds for information technology. We are therefore unable to advise on the volume or type of equipment that has been purchased. Headteachers manage their own budgets, prioritise spend and are best placed to decide on local requirements.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390750/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T11:51:27.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390750/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390750/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Schools: ICT","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department has spent on (a) tablet computers and (b) other new information technology for students in schools in (i) 2012-13 and (ii) 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Jason McCartney","Colne Valley","Jason McCartney","7554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390751","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>The number of children who have been placed in children’s homes outside their local authority area in each of the last five years, 2010 to 2014, is shown in the table below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of children accommodated in children homes outside council boundary at 31 March</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>2,350</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>2,390</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2,730</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This information is published in table A3 of the statistical first release “Children looked after in England including adoption”, which is available online at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/children-looked-after-in-england-including-adoption--2</a></p><p> </p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390751/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:32:47.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390751/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390751/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in care have been placed in children's homes outside their local authority area in each of the last five years.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","7603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390752","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>Looked-after children should only be placed far from home where this is in their best interests. To improve practice in this area the Government has amended regulations so that:</p><ul><li>the Director of Children’s Services must approve that the decision to place a child at a distance from their home is the best decision for the child and that there will be ongoing support for them;</li><li>the local authority making the placement must consult with the authority in which the home is located before making the decision to place the child there. This consultation should include the quality of the home and the services available for the child.</li></ul>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390752/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T09:44:05.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390752/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390752/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Children in Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she has taken to reduce the number of children in care placed out of their home local authority area.","true","Biography information for Tim Loughton","East Worthing and Shoreham","Tim Loughton","7604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390753","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The government has no plans to introduce Chartered Teacher status. We are committed to supporting the work to establish a College of Teaching, an independent professional body for teachers. A consortium of education organisations is working to establish the College, and is considering whether the College could award Chartered Teacher status to members who have completed a programme of professional development. However, such operational decisions are the responsibility of the independent organisation itself, and not for the government to determine.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390753/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T10:14:21.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390753/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390753/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on introducing chartered teacher status within the education profession; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390754","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The government is improving the capacity for schools to take the lead in training and developing their teachers through the national network of Teaching School Alliances. This network is leading collaboration between schools and helping to make professional development more effective, which in turn is helping teachers to improve.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The government expects teachers’ professional development to be increasingly led by schools and teachers. Schools and headteachers are best placed to determine which development activities will be most beneficial for their schools. To help them do this, the government has established an independent Teachers’ Professional Development Expert Group – chaired by David Weston, Chief Executive of the Teacher Development Trust – to develop a new standard for teachers’ professional development. The new standard will complement the existing ‘Teachers’ Standards’, and help teachers and schools to understand what makes professional development most effective.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390754/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T09:53:35.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390754/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390754/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to improve skills within the teaching profession; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390755","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>As part of our programme to develop a school-led system, the government supports the development of excellent school leadership, together with high-quality teaching. Professional development for schools leaders, to support and develop excellent leadership, is therefore important.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Professional Qualification for Headship (NPQH) enables headteachers to develop their skills in areas such as leading and improving teaching, leading an effective school and leading change for improvement. A range of short programmes are also available to headteachers to support their development, either through school-led providers of the NPQH or through self-study modules available via the National Archives located within the GOV.uk website.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National College for Teaching and Leadership recently piloted a Multi-Academy Trust Leadership Programme. This had a heavy emphasis on high-level business and strategic finance skills in recognition of the fact that the need for leadership and business skills varies considerably between leading a single school, and running a chain of five or more schools.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A review of headteacher standards, chaired by Dame Dana Ross-Wawrzynski, was launched by the Department for Education on 17 April 2014. It brought together a group of respected professionals, including headteachers, to create new standards for the sector. The standards set out the behaviour, qualities and knowledge expected of today’s headteachers. The new National Standards of Excellence for Headteachers were published in January 2015 and are available online at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-standards-of-excellence-for-headteachers" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-standards-of-excellence-for-headteachers</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>System leaders also provide support for improving the leadership skills of headteachers. For example, ‘local leaders of education’ work outside their own school, providing support to another headteacher and their school. The two headteachers work together to plan and implement improvements.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390755/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T10:15:06.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390755/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390755/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Headteachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she is taking to improve the leadership skills of head teachers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","7640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390756","Department for Education","false","2015-07-23","<p>The table below shows the number of pupils identified as gifted and talented in the Copeland constituency for the years in which data is available. The data was not collected until 2007 and has not been collected since 2011.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Gifted &amp; Talented Pupils</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Pupils in Constituency</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Percentage Gifted &amp; Talented</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>1,114</p></td><td><p>12,838</p></td><td><p>8.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>1,112</p></td><td><p>12,187</p></td><td><p>9.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>1,035</p></td><td><p>11,918</p></td><td><p>8.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>1,003</p></td><td><p>11,461</p></td><td><p>8.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>1,047</p></td><td><p>11,116</p></td><td><p>9.4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390756/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T10:13:56.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390756/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390756/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Gifted Children: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children in Copeland constituency have been identified as gifted and talented in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","7633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390757","Department for Education","false","2015-07-21","<p>From September 2015, childcare provision in Sure Start children’s centres and early years settings will be inspected on the same basis as primary and secondary schools under Ofsted’s new Common Inspection Framework. For the first time the full range of education settings will be inspected to a common set of rigorous standards, giving parents better information on quality. Details of the Common Inspection Framework are available on the Ofsted website at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/changes-to-education-inspection-from-september-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/changes-to-education-inspection-from-september-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>We will be consulting in the autumn on wider children’s centre services and working with Ofsted on the most appropriate accountability regime for them.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390757/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:02:05.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390757/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390757/answer",,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-07-16","Pre-school Education: Inspections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to make Ofsted inspections of (a) children's centres and (b) other early years settings as rigorous as inspection of primary and secondary schools.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390758","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-21","<p>DECC has not published any such guidance. Quality and standards for solar PV are administered by the Micro-generation Certification Scheme (MCS) which certifies installers under the MCS Certificate and Renewable Energy Consumer Code (RECC).</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390758/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:25:55.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390758/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390758/answer",,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-16","Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what guidance her Department has published on the effect of loft extensions on the installation of solar roof panels.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","7692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390759","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Government is committed to securing an ambitious, legally binding, global deal on climate change at the Conference of the Parties (COP) 21 to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) in Paris in December.</p><p>With other countries we are making steady progress to secure an ambitious global deal in Paris. My rt. hon. Friends the Prime Minister and the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change are actively engaging in preparations for Paris. Alongside other G7 leaders, the Prime Minister called for priority to be given to delivering an ambitious climate agreement at this year’s COP. The G7 statement included strong language on the need for a deal in Paris, on climate finance and on future ambition. The endorsement by G7 leaders has provided further positive momentum. The Secretary of State has also met her international counterparts to discuss the key issues for the Conference in Paris on several occasions, including at the Petersburg Dialogue in Berlin, at the G7 Climate Ministers meeting, the EU Environment Council, and most recently at the Major Economies Forum on Energy and Climate Change in Luxembourg last week.</p><p>Intended Nationally Determined Contributions covering 46 countries have been received, including from the EU, US, China, South Korea, Mexico, Russia and Canada, covering over 58% of emissions. The UK is calling for the pace of negotiations to accelerate and actively encouraging other countries to come forward with ambitious INDCs as soon as possible.</p><p>There remains a lot of work to do. But my Ministerial colleagues and I will take every opportunity to press for an agreement which includes greenhouse gas reduction targets from all countries that together keep the global goal of limiting global warming to 2 degrees within reach, a regular review of targets and a global long term goal, and a set of rules that ensure transparency and accountability of commitments and allows the world to track progress.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390759/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T15:27:47.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390759/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390759/answer",,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-16","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what progress has been made on (a) negotiation on and (b) preparations for the November 2015 climate change conference; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","7679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390760","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-21","<p>Rivers can supply renewable energy in two main ways: they can provide hydro-electric power, and they can provide heat for water-sourced heat pumps.</p><p>The Department published a digital water source heat map in March 2015. The map estimates the potential thermal capacity of rivers, estuaries, canals and coastal sites in England. The map seeks to raise awareness of this potential source of renewable heat which can be utilised through the deployment of water source heat pumps supplying district heating networks and other users.</p><p>The map estimates the total heat capacity from the River Ouse at 505 Megawatts, enough to potentially heat 74,000 homes, subject to environmental and other location-specific consents.</p><p>Water source heat pumps are eligible for support through the Renewable Heat Incentive and heat network projects taken forward by Local Authorities can apply for support from the Heat Network Delivery Unit.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390760/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T11:04:03.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390760/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390760/answer",,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-16","River Ouse: Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential use of the River Ouse as a source of renewable energy.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390761","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Government will be guided by the fuel poverty strategy published in March 2015 which sets out a clear policy of working towards improving energy efficiency standards across the English housing stock, including in the homes of the fuel poor. The strategy highlighted a concern relating to issues faced by park home residents in keeping their homes warm. Therefore, the Government is undertaking further research and working with stakeholders to understand the drivers of fuel poverty in park homes.</p><p>DECC has also been ensuring park homes residents are able to benefit from our existing schemes targeted at the fuel poor such as the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) and Warm Home Discount (WHD).</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390761/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T17:00:12.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390761/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390761/answer",,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-16","Fuel Poverty: Mobile Homes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to ensure that the fuel poverty strategy benefits people living in park homes.","false","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","7569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390762","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-07-21","<p>The Department is aware of this report. As with the many reports and papers that are published on nuclear energy, DECC officials are examining the report to determine if there is any new information presented that the Government should take into consideration.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390762/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T11:15:10.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390762/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390762/answer",,,,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-07-16","Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the World Nuclear Industry Status Report 2015 published on 15 July 2015; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","7564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390763","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-21","<p>Estimates of the carbon savings from regulation on housebuilders in England have been included in the Updated Emissions Projections published by the Department of Energy and Climate Change. The Government will be taking into account changes in policy in the next update of those projections.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390763/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T16:57:49.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390763/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390763/answer",,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-16","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to section 9.17 of Fixing the foundations: creating a more prosperous nation, published on 10 July 2015, Cm 9098, what impact assessment his Department has made of any impact assessment of reducing net regulation on housebuilders on meeting climate change targets.","false","Biography information for Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","City of Durham","Dr Roberta Blackman-Woods","7724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390764","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-21","<p>A ban on the use of wild animals in travelling circuses is a manifesto commitment and will be introduced as soon as parliamentary time allows. In the interim, the welfare of the 18 wild animals still being used by travelling circuses in England is protected by the Welfare of Wild Animals in Travelling Circuses (England) Regulations 2012</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390764/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T13:44:46.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390764/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390764/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Animal Welfare: Circuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she intends to bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit the use of wild animals in circuses.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","7749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390765","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-21","<p>One of the most significant changes in the reformed Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) is the introduction of a landing obligation which prohibits the discarding of fish.</p><p>The Government believes that fishermen should be able to maximise the value of all the catch they land. Fish that can go to human consumption routes will be the most profitable. The industry organisation Seafish has led work into why certain fish species are discarded, how they can be brought to market and so drive value for fishermen.</p><p>Fish that are undersize (below Minimum Conservation Reference Size) can be directed to non-direct human consumption markets such as fish meal, fish oil, bait, pet food, food additives, pharmaceuticals, cosmetics and digestion. We are currently working with different parts of the fishing industry to ensure they can access these markets and to help them find practical solutions to the challenges of managing undersize catch onshore. Information on this will be issued to the industry in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390765/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T10:18:41.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390765/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390765/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on the discard of fish which can no longer be discarded lawfully at sea on land, and the potential utilisation of such fish; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Christopher Chope","Christchurch","Mr Christopher Chope","7585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390766","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-23","<p>Defra Ministers have received various representations from New Covent Garden Market tenants in the past five years about the market redevelopment.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These have taken the form of formal correspondence and face to face meetings between the Covent Garden Tenants Association (CGTA) and the Minister, held at Defra and at New Covent Garden Market.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The representations have addressed a broad range of concerns about the plans for the redevelopment, its implementation and the role of the CGMA.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390766/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T11:25:44.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390766/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390766/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Covent Garden Market Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has received from tenants of the New Covent Garden market Authority on that market's redevelopment in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390767","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-21","<p>The positions of the principal officers of the Covent Garden Market Authority are:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Mrs J Lloyd - Chief Executive Officer</p><p> </p><p>Mr C Morton - Finance Director/Authority Secretary</p><p> </p><p>Mr B Marlow - Operations Director</p><p> </p><p>Mr C Townend - Project Director</p><p> </p><p>Ms H Evans - Business development &amp; Support Director</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Their annual gross pay in the last 5 years is shown below:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2010/11</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mrs Lloyd</strong></p></td><td><p>198,316</p></td><td><p>172,110</p></td><td><p>227,249</p></td><td><p>191,715</p></td><td><p>222,569</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mr Morton</strong></p></td><td><p>154,979</p></td><td><p>147,978</p></td><td><p>164,772</p></td><td><p>151,199</p></td><td><p>166,977</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mr Marlow</strong></p></td><td><p>98,471</p></td><td><p>100,543</p></td><td><p>108,600</p></td><td><p>112,218</p></td><td><p>120,361</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Mr Townend</strong></p></td><td><p>n/a</p></td><td><p>n/a</p></td><td><p>89,146</p></td><td><p>117,240</p></td><td><p>127,898</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Ms Evans</strong></p></td><td><p>n/a</p></td><td><p>62,626</p></td><td><p>75,511</p></td><td><p>81,828</p></td><td><p>99,300</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The remuneration policy for the principal officers is recommended and monitored by CGMA’s Remuneration Committee. A representative of Defra attends the Committee but is not a member of the Committee. The pay is set by the CGMA Board.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The position and pay of each of the principal officers is reported in CGMA’s Annual Report &amp; Accounts, copies of which have been laid in the libraries of the Houses of Parliament.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390767/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-21T14:44:04.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390767/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390767/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Covent Garden Market Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what the (a) positions and (b) pay were of the principal officers of the New Covent Garden Market Authority in the last five years; and what consultation process will take place before any pay increases are awarded.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390768","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-23","<p>There has been no sale of land by CGMA in the last five years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>However, as part of the development of the new Northern Line extension, London Underground Limited has occupied CGMA’s former office building, Covent House, under a Transport and Works order which allows them to do so on a temporary basis. CGMA has entered into a Transport and Works Agreement with London Underground Limited, conditional on the issue of a general vesting declaration to effect the sale of the land to London Underground Limited. It is anticipated this will complete in August 2015. CGMA will receive £10.4m for the sale of Covent House and the full amount will subsequently be transferred to Defra.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390768/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T11:38:27.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390768/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390768/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Covent Garden Market Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what receipts the New Covent Garden Market Authority has received from the sale of land in the last five years; who bought the land in each such case; and for what purpose the land was sold in each such case.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390769","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-23","<p>The existing Multi storey car park has been assessed by structural engineers from both the Covent Garden Market Authority (CGMA) and by CGMA’s Private Development Partner who consider the structure to be in a satisfactory condition to be retained and refurbished rather than demolished and rebuilt. However, due to the age of the car park, additional works are required to bring the user environment and services up to current standards. As such, repairs are being carried out to the concrete decks and walls, all surfaces are being treated with specialist paint finishes, new handrails are being installed and all electrical and mechanical services including two passenger lifts are being replaced. Externally, as required by a planning condition, a green wall is being installed to half of the surface area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The contracts to undertake the work will be let by the Private Development Partner, VSM (NCGM) Limited. Some of these contracts have yet to be finalised and as such cost information is commercially confidential and cannot be disclosed at this time.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390769/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T12:04:06.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390769/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390769/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","New Covent Garden Market","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how much the demolition and rebuilding of the car park in New Covent Garden Market is forecast to cost.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390770","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-07-23","<p>The total expenses claimed by the Board of the Covent Garden Market Authority for each of the last five years were:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>2010/11 £9,394</p><p> </p><p>2011/12 £11,139</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 £9,791</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 £5,345</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 £6,451</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The amounts predominantly relate to travel and accommodation expenses associated with attendance at Board and Committee meetings.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390770/answer",,,,,,"2015-07-23T11:32:48.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390770/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/390770/answer",,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-07-16","Covent Garden Market Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what expenses have been claimed by the directors of the New Covent Garden Market Authority in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","7644"
